public class LoopsExample {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        // For loop — count from 1 to 5
        System.out.println("=== For Loop ===");
        for (int i = 1; i <= 5; i++) {
            System.out.println("Count: " + i);
        }

        // While loop — add numbers until sum > 20
        System.out.println("=== While Loop ===");
        int sum = 0;
        int counter = 1;
        while (sum <= 20) {
            sum += counter;
            System.out.println("Adding " + counter + ", sum = " + sum);
            counter++;
        }

        // Do-while — runs at least once
        System.out.println("=== Do-While Loop ===");
        int num = 0;
        do {
            System.out.println("This runs at least once! num = " + num);
            num++;
        } while (num < 3);

        // Break and continue
        System.out.println("=== Break & Continue ===");
        for (int i = 1; i <= 10; i++) {
            if (i == 6) {
                System.out.println("Breaking at " + i);
                break;  // Exits loop
            }
            if (i % 2 == 0) {
                continue;  // Skips even numbers
            }
            System.out.println("Odd number: " + i);
        }
    }
}

phase1.explanation:
Loops repeat code multiple times:

For loop: when you know how many times to repeat
for (initialization; condition; increment) {
    // code to repeat
}

While loop: when you need to loop until a condition changes
while (condition) {
    // code to repeat
}

Do-while: ALWAYS runs at least once, then checks condition
do {
    // code to repeat at least once
} while (condition);

Loop control:
• break — exits the loop completely
• continue — skips to the next iteration

⚠️ Be careful with infinite loops: while (true) without a break is dangerous!

